# Web App Instructions

## Project
A Next.js 14 web application using the App Router, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS,
and Prisma ORM with PostgreSQL. State management uses Zustand for client state
and React Query for server state. UI components are from shadcn/ui.

## Commands
- Start dev server: `npm run dev`
- Run tests: `npm test`
- Run e2e tests: `npx playwright test`
- Type check: `npm run type-check`
- Lint: `npm run lint`
- Build: `npm run build`
- Database migration: `npx prisma migrate dev`
- Open Prisma Studio: `npx prisma studio`

## Code Style
- Strict TypeScript — no `any`, prefer `unknown` for truly unknown types
- Use `'` for string literals, not `"`
- Components: named exports, not default exports (except page.tsx and layout.tsx)
- File names: `kebab-case.tsx` for components, `camelCase.ts` for utilities
- Tailwind classes: group by category (layout, spacing, typography, color)
- Use `cn()` from `lib/utils` for conditional class merging

## Architecture
- `/app` — Next.js App Router pages and layouts
- `/components` — Reusable UI components (shadcn/ui base components in `/components/ui`)
- `/lib` — Utilities, API clients, and shared logic
- `/server` — Server-only code (database queries, server actions)
- Server Components by default; add `'use client'` only when needed (event handlers, hooks)
- Database access only from `/server` — never import Prisma in client components

## API and Data
- Server Actions for mutations — no separate API routes for simple CRUD
- API routes (`/app/api`) only for webhooks, external integrations, or streaming
- Use React Query for data that needs client-side caching/invalidation
- Prisma queries go in `/server/db/` — never inline in components

## Testing
- Unit tests with Vitest for utilities and pure functions
- Component tests with React Testing Library for interactive UI
- Playwright for critical user flows (auth, checkout, core actions)

## Do Not
- Import server-only modules in client components (Prisma, fs, crypto secrets)
- Use `useEffect` for data fetching — use Server Components or React Query
- Add inline styles — everything through Tailwind
- Use `<img>` — always use Next.js `<Image>` for automatic optimization
